00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,000
 Right here?

2
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:02,000
 All right.

3
00:00:02,000 --> 00:00:03,000
 Okay.

4
00:00:03,000 --> 00:00:06,000
 Today we're going to look at a passage that I had asked Kelly.

5
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:08,000
 I said, "Hey, Kelly, when was the last time you preached this passage?"

6
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:14,000
 Because I wanted to make sure that it's been two years since we looked at Judges chapter 6.

7
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:18,000
 And when I first looked at the story of Judges 6 with Gideon,

8
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:23,000
 we looked at the idea of tearing down the altars and putting the proper altar in its place.

9
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:28,000
 But today we're going to talk about a topic that I think applies to every single one of us in the room,

10
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:31,000
 is the idea of work.

11
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:37,000
 60% of all of our time throughout the entire week is spent at a job.

12
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:41,000
 And a lot of times within that job, some of us may love what we do.

13
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:48,000
 Some of us may just sit in there and say, "Man, is this all there is to my life? I hate my job."

14
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:56,000
 And we're left wondering, "Lord, what is it that you're calling us to do in the idea of work?"

15
00:00:56,000 --> 00:00:59,000
 Faith, work, integration is so important for us as Christ followers

16
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:05,000
 because we do that all the time for a good chunk of the rest of our lives.

17
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:07,000
 We're at work until you decide to retire.

18
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:14,000
 Whether it's at 60 or whether it's 75 or 80 years old, you will be working.

19
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:19,000
 And I wish that some of us were probably sitting there, could be like David,

20
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:23,000
 where Samuel calls out and is trying to select the next king.

21
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:28,000
 And David shows up and he whispers to David, "You're going to be the next king."

22
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:31,000
 But it doesn't always happen, does it?

23
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:38,000
 Some of us are like Joseph, where we kind of land in exactly at a time when God uses us.

24
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:44,000
 Joseph is a guy that for some odd reason, his brother sold him into slavery.

25
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:46,000
 And now he is a slave.

26
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:53,000
 And somehow or another, God has given him the skills to rise up in the ranks in the palace

27
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:55,000
 of where he sold in slavery.

28
00:01:55,000 --> 00:02:02,000
 But then his boss's wife accuses him of sexual malpractice and that he's thrown into prison.

29
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:05,000
 And later on, because of all the things that are happening,

30
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:10,000
 he rises up to be the chief of staff in the political system.

31
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:15,000
 Some of us are like Nehemiah, who is a cupbearer to the king.

32
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:19,000
 He tastes food so that the king, his boss, doesn't get poisoned.

33
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:24,000
 And somehow or another, God uses the cupbearer to the king

34
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:29,000
 to then rebuild the walls of Jerusalem because he has given him that burden.

35
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:34,000
 Or then some of us look at the two tax collectors in the Gospels.

36
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:37,000
 There's the tax collector of Matthew, where Jesus says to Matthew,

37
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:39,000
 "Pack up everything and follow me."

38
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:45,000
 But yet at the same time, he says to Zacchaeus, who climbs up a tree to see him,

39
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:50,000
 "I want you to follow me by staying as a tax collector."

40
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:52,000
 So how do you know when to be a tax collector?

41
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:54,000
 How do you know when to drop everything and follow Jesus?

42
00:02:54,000 --> 00:02:56,000
 How do you know when to be a king?

43
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:58,000
 How do you know when to do all these different things?

44
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:00,000
 All of us are on the journey, aren't we?

45
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:04,000
 Some of us are called to be like Pastor Mark is a full-time vocational ministry.

46
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:08,000
 Some people are called to be a stay-at-home mom.

47
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:10,000
 Some people are called to be a teacher or a nurse.

48
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:13,000
 Some people are called to be an engineer, an entrepreneur.

49
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:17,000
 How do we begin to know what God has gifted us to be?

50
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:21,000
 And it becomes a journey that he leads all of us on.

51
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:27,000
 And sometimes within the journey, there's different chapters in our life within that journey.

52
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:31,000
 And within those chapters, is that where you want me to be?

53
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:35,000
 Maybe, but maybe not.

54
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:41,000
 And so sometimes he'll ask us to pivot, and 20 years from now, we'll look back at our life and say,

55
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:45,000
 "Wow, that's what you've been preparing me for."

56
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:50,000
 I think I've told all of you guys I spent the first 10 years of my life building cell towers.

57
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:54,000
 Then from that point on, I spent about three years working in a Korean church,

58
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:57,000
 while at the same time, also at that point in time before that,

59
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:01,000
 serving in a church over in Chinatown at CCUC.

60
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:05,000
 And then from that point, I worked at Moody Bible Institute for a number of three years.

61
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:08,000
 And then now for the last 10 years, I work at Resource Global,

62
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:11,000
 and Wheaton College, Northern Seminary for a period of time.

63
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:14,000
 Lord, is that what you're calling me to do?

64
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:18,000
 I thought it was building cell towers, or rather that.

65
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:21,000
 I went to college thinking I was going to medical school.

66
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:24,000
 God calls us to do different things.

67
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:28,000
 So today, he calls this particular person,

68
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:31,000
 and we're going to look at that person,

69
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:34,000
 and we're going to glean some stories that he talks in.

70
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:41,000
 What the whole idea is, what is God calling you to do right now?

71
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:46,000
 And can you and I be faithful to where God has placed us in?

72
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:51,000
 Because God, for a period of time, has called you at that point in time,

73
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:57,000
 at that point in place, to make a difference for the gospel.

74
00:04:57,000 --> 00:04:59,000
 We start in Judges 6.

75
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:02,000
 I studied this for a number of years.

76
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:05,000
 And it is such a powerful--it begins with this whole idea,

77
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:09,000
 "The people of Israel did what was evil in the sight of the Lord.

78
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:13,000
 And the Lord gave them into the hand of Midian for seven years.

79
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:15,000
 And the hand of Midian overpowered Israel.

80
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:18,000
 And because of Midian, the people of Israel made for themselves

81
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:22,000
 the debris that are in the mountains and the caves and the strongholds.

82
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:26,000
 For whenever the Israelites planted crops to Midianites and the Amalekites

83
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:30,000
 and the people of the east would come up against them.

84
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:35,000
 They would encamp against them and devour the produce of the land as far as Gaza

85
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:40,000
 and leave no sustenance in Israel and no sheep or ox or donkey.

86
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:45,000
 For they would come up with their livestock in their tents.

87
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:49,000
 They would come like locusts in numbers.

88
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:52,000
 Both they and their camels could not be counted,

89
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:56,000
 so that they laid waste to land as they came in.

90
00:05:56,000 --> 00:05:59,000
 And Israel was brought very low because of Midian.

91
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:02,000
 And the people of Israel cried out for help in the Lord.

92
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:09,000
 Don't ever misinterpret how God uses events in our life to turn us back to him.

93
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:13,000
 And too often with the Israelites, time and time and time again,

94
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:17,000
 the Israelites go and do whatever they want to do.

95
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:23,000
 But yet God uses situations and circumstances in our life

96
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:26,000
 to call and draw us back to them.

97
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:31,000
 And some of those circumstances may be trials in hard times.

98
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:36,000
 And here we see an example of that in the hands of the Midian.

99
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:41,000
 When the people of Israel in John chapter, Judges chapter 6, verse 7,

100
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:45,000
 when the people of Israel cried out to the Lord on count of the Midianites,

101
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:49,000
 the Lord sent a prophet to the people of Israel, and he said to them,

102
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:51,000
 "Thus says the Lord, the God of Israel,

103
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:56,000
 'I led you up from Egypt and brought you out of the house of bondage,

104
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:59,000
 and I delivered you from the hands of the Egyptians

105
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:02,000
 and from the hand of all who oppressed you,

106
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:05,000
 and drove them out before you and gave you their land.

107
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:08,000
 And I said to you, 'I am the Lord your God,

108
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:13,000
 and you shall not fear the gods of the Amorites in whose land you dwell,

109
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:17,000
 but you have not obeyed my voice.'"

110
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:21,000
 And now the angel of the Lord, when the angel of the Lord appears,

111
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:26,000
 you listen to him, "came and sat down on the terebth at Oprah," in verse 11,

112
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:28,000
 "which belonged to Joash the Abyssalite,

113
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:32,000
 while his son Gideon was beating out wheat in the winepress

114
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:33,000
 to hide it from the Midianites."

115
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:37,000
 And here's a key verse, and we've looked at it before, verse 12,

116
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:40,000
 "And the angel of the Lord appeared to him and says to him,

117
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:43,000
 'The Lord is with you, O mighty man of valor.'"

118
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:51,000
 In verse 12, "The Lord says to him, 'The Lord is with you, O mighty man of valor.'"

119
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:55,000
 If you were to look at the NIV, I'm reading from the ESV,

120
00:07:55,000 --> 00:08:00,000
 if you were to look at the NIV, it says, "O mighty, mighty warrior."

121
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:06,000
 "The Lord is with you, O mighty warrior."

122
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:10,000
 And when you're looking at that, your first thought is,

123
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:16,000
 "Wait a minute, Lord, why are you calling him a mighty warrior?"

124
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:20,000
 That is the verse that sticks out.

125
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:25,000
 Why is the angel of the Lord calling him a mighty warrior?

126
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:27,000
 Why is that?

127
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:33,000
 He's threshing wheat in a winepress.

128
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:37,000
 That and being a mighty warrior don't go hand in hand.

129
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:40,000
 And you're wondering why.

130
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:44,000
 Because if you go into it, it's harvest time, right?

131
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:47,000
 It is harvest time, the wheat is ready to be harvested,

132
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:51,000
 and you're pulling out all of the wheat, and you pull out all the stalks

133
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:55,000
 and everything like that, and you usually grab all your wheat,

134
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:59,000
 and you lay out on top of a threshing floor.

135
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:04,000
 And a threshing floor is usually an inclined space out in the open,

136
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:07,000
 on a hill and everything like that, and you'll understand exactly what it is,

137
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:10,000
 and you'll lay out all your wheat on the threshing floor.

138
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:14,000
 And from that point on, if you have a lot of wheat, you'll get your oxen,

139
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:16,000
 you'll get your horses, you'll get all that stuff,

140
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:19,000
 and you're going to stomp on it, stomp on it, stomp on it.

141
00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:23,000
 If you have a tiny little harvest, you'll take a little flail or hammer,

142
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:27,000
 and you sit there and you'll hit the wheat over and over and over again,

143
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:32,000
 and it separates the stalks and it separates the head.

144
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:35,000
 And from that point on, once you do that, remember it's out in the open,

145
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:39,000
 you'll take a little rake or a winnowing fork, and you'll sit there

146
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:42,000
 and you'll lift it high and you'll throw it high up in the air.

147
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:44,000
 And it separates the two areas.

148
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:50,000
 It separates the heavier grain on one side and the straw on the other side.

149
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:54,000
 And then there's seed covering the chaff, and as you're throwing it up

150
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:59,000
 with this winnowing fork, it's blowing all over.

151
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:03,000
 And that's why it has to be up on an inclined space out in the open

152
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:08,000
 where there's a lot of breeze that blows everything away.

153
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:12,000
 And that is threshing wheat on the threshing floor.

154
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:17,000
 But where is this guy at? He's in--what? He's threshing wheat where?

155
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:21,000
 In a wine press. What's a wine press?

156
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:27,000
 It's literally a hole, a rectangular hole, in which when I stand in there,

157
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:32,000
 it goes up to my waist, and you lay out all your grapes right there.

158
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:35,000
 And you sit there and you stomp on it.

159
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:40,000
 And there's a little hole which leads to a set of cisterns or jars

160
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:41,000
 and everything like that.

161
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:44,000
 And as soon as you sit there and you stomp on it and you stomp on it

162
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:48,000
 and you stomp on it, all the juice rolls into a cistern.

163
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:52,000
 But yet it's not an inclined space.

164
00:10:52,000 --> 00:10:56,000
 And yet he is threshing wheat. In where?

165
00:10:56,000 --> 00:10:59,000
 In a wine press.

166
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:04,000
 And the angel of the Lord, the Lord, the angel of the Lord calls him,

167
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:09,000
 "The Lord is with you, mighty warrior."

168
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:12,000
 And when you're sitting there in verse 12, looking at it,

169
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:19,000
 you're sitting there, "Okay, Lord, what are you seeing?

170
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:23,000
 He's not a mighty warrior.

171
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:27,000
 He's afraid. He's a coward.

172
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:32,000
 So why are you calling him a mighty warrior?"

173
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:35,000
 Two things, two things, two very important things.

174
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:41,000
 Number one, the Lord sees you differently.

175
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:48,000
 The how you see yourself and not how others see you.

176
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:52,000
 The Lord sees you differently to how you see yourself

177
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:56,000
 and how others see you.

178
00:11:56,000 --> 00:12:02,000
 The Lord sees in him Gideon, a mighty warrior.

179
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:07,000
 We see in him a guy who's afraid.

180
00:12:07,000 --> 00:12:12,000
 That's why he's threshing wheat on the wine press.

181
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:15,000
 We see a guy who's scared.

182
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:19,000
 We see a guy who lacks courage.

183
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:23,000
 And we don't understand what God is trying to say to him.

184
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:27,000
 "The Lord is with you, almighty man of valor.

185
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:31,000
 The Lord is with you, mighty warrior." Yes!

186
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:36,000
 Because God sees you differently

187
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:41,000
 to how you see yourselves and how others see you.

188
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:43,000
 That's number one.

189
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:49,000
 Number two, in terms of this, God has a name for you.

190
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:52,000
 God has a purpose for you.

191
00:12:52,000 --> 00:12:57,000
 God has a vision for you.

192
00:12:57,000 --> 00:13:05,000
 For Gideon was a mighty man of valor, mighty warrior.

193
00:13:05,000 --> 00:13:10,000
 What's the name that he has for you?

194
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:16,000
 What's the name that you believe that he's calling you to be?

195
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:20,000
 If we all sat here in a group and had an exercise

196
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:22,000
 and we got a chance to brag each other,

197
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:25,000
 and I know a lot of times primarily with us Asians

198
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:27,000
 and other stuff is we don't like to talk,

199
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:30,000
 we don't like to brag about ourselves,

200
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:36,000
 but we are familiar with what skills and gifts we do have.

201
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:40,000
 What's the name that he's given to you?

202
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:46,000
 What vision does he have for your life?

203
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:50,000
 For Gideon is the mighty warrior.

204
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:54,000
 Maybe for Mark, a lot of times, it's leadership

205
00:13:54,000 --> 00:13:59,000
 or it's shepherding or something like that, administrative.

206
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:02,000
 Maybe it's the ability to convene people.

207
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:04,000
 Maybe it's the ability to inspire people.

208
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:07,000
 Maybe it's the ability to build together a team

209
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:09,000
 or whatever it is.

210
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:12,000
 Maybe a lot of times your intellect is so brilliant

211
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:14,000
 because that's how God is going to--

212
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:17,000
 he's using you to do things and change education.

213
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:21,000
 Maybe it's because your skill, you're going to change healthcare.

214
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:25,000
 Whatever it is, what is that vision?

215
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:31,000
 Maybe it's being an engineer to create innovative tools.

216
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:36,000
 What is that vision in your life?

217
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:40,000
 As we continue to seek the Lord,

218
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:44,000
 what is he calling us in our life?

219
00:14:44,000 --> 00:14:47,000
 There's this one lady that I got a chance to meet.

220
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:51,000
 She's Filipino, and if you came, she's very quiet,

221
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:54,000
 and she would just sit there, and you probably wouldn't even know her.

222
00:14:54,000 --> 00:14:56,000
 Her name is Nikki.

223
00:14:56,000 --> 00:15:01,000
 But what you don't know about Nikki is she is a brilliant lady.

224
00:15:01,000 --> 00:15:06,000
 She is extremely talented, teaches part-time at Stanford University.

225
00:15:06,000 --> 00:15:11,000
 Then she's an entrepreneur, started working in education,

226
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:15,000
 worked in colleges and universities and the executive level,

227
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:18,000
 but then she started realizing she doesn't have a medical degree

228
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:19,000
 and all that stuff.

229
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:23,000
 She was great at entrepreneurial things.

230
00:15:23,000 --> 00:15:28,000
 She was great at starting up and launching different ideas.

231
00:15:28,000 --> 00:15:30,000
 Now she teaches part-time at Stanford.

232
00:15:30,000 --> 00:15:37,000
 She's the founding CEO of a company that is working with

